## **1.8 Essential Grammatical Elements in ggplot2: stat**

### **1.8.1 Working with `stat()`**


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data, 
       aes(y = MATHS, x= GENDER)) +
  geom_boxplot()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](HO_EX01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-20-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


### **1.8.2 Working with stat - the *stat_summary()* method**


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data, 
       aes(y = MATHS, x= GENDER)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  stat_summary(geom = "point",       
               fun = "mean",         
               colour ="red",        
               size=4)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](HO_EX01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-21-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


### **1.8.3 Working with stat - the `geom()` method**


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data, 
       aes(y = MATHS, x= GENDER)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_point(stat="summary",        
             fun="mean",           
             colour="red",          
             size=4) 
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](HO_EX01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-22-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


### **1.8.4 Adding a best fit curve on a scatterplot?**

The scatterplot below shows the relationship of Maths and English grades of pupils. The interpretability of this graph can be improved by adding a best fit curve.

![](images/scatterplot.png){width="516"}

In the code chunk below, geom_smooth() is used to plot a best fit curve on the scatterplot.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data, 
       aes(x= MATHS, y=ENGLISH)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(size=0.5)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](HO_EX01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-23-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


The default smoothing method can be overridden as shown below.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data, 
       aes(x= MATHS, 
           y=ENGLISH)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method=lm, 
              linewidth=0.5)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](HO_EX01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-24-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


## **1.9 Essential Grammatical Elements in ggplot2: Facets**

### **1.9.1 Working with `facet_wrap()`**


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data, 
       aes(x= MATHS)) +
  geom_histogram(bins=20) +
    facet_wrap(~ CLASS)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](HO_EX01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-25-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


### **1.9.2 `facet_grid()` function**


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data, 
       aes(x= MATHS)) +
  geom_histogram(bins=20) +
    facet_grid(~ CLASS)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](HO_EX01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-26-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


## **1.10 Essential Grammatical Elements in ggplot2: Coordinates**

### **1.10.1 Working with Coordinate**


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data, 
       aes(x=RACE)) +
  geom_bar()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](HO_EX01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-27-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


The code chunk below flips the horizontal bar chart into vertical bar chart by using coord_flip().


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data, 
       aes(x=RACE)) +
  geom_bar() +
  coord_flip()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](HO_EX01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-28-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


### **1.10.2 Changing the y- and x-axis range**


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data, 
       aes(x= MATHS, y=ENGLISH)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method=lm, size=0.5)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](HO_EX01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-29-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


The code chunk below fixed both the y-axis and x-axis range from 0-100.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data, 
       aes(x= MATHS, y=ENGLISH)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method=lm, 
              size=0.5) +  
  coord_cartesian(xlim=c(0,100),
                  ylim=c(0,100))
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](HO_EX01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-30-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


